On January 21st 2021 I saw a large herd of around 10 white-tail deer (Odocoileus virginianus). The weather that day was windy but very sunny. The temperature at the time I saw these deer was 43° F, with the high for the day being 43 and the low being 21. It was not currently precipitating at the time I saw the deer but there was snow on the ground from a previous snow. You could tell these were white-tail deer because of the white fur on the underside of their tales and the brown and white coloring of their coats. The only other species I saw was a grey squirrel (Sciurus carolinensis), but unfortunately it was moving way too fast for me to get a good photo of it. The herd of deer were just grazing around through the fallen leaves looking for food. What was really interesting though in the photo I've included (iNaturalist wouldn't let me upload the video I had) is that one of the deer found what seemed to me to be bread. It was shaking it's head back and forth to try and break it up as it was eating it. In another photo I've included you can see some of the herd running away, and you can really see the white tail. They are kind of hard to see because they blend in with the trees but I promise they are there.

This is a Northern Cardinal (Cardinalis cardinalis) because of the bird's distinct red feathers that stand out and black feathers around the beak. The weather was cloudy with a high of  34 degrees and a low of 30 degrees, the humidity was 79%, the wind was NW 12 mph. This bird was on an Eastern Redbud (Cercis canadensis) that was next to a bird feeder so the bird was probably checking the available seeds. The Eastern Redbud was full of rosy-purple flower buds but it is hard to see in the pictures. It is another thing to note that this cardinal is a male because only male cardinals have all red feathers like this.

This observation is of the Shaggy Mane Mushroom (Coprinus comatus). The Shaggy Mane Mushroom can be identified by its 5-15 cm conical cap, brown recurved scales, and white color. I first came across this mushroom a few weeks ago right outside the employee entrance of the PPG Aquarium along the sidewalk. With some assistance I later identified it as the Shaggy Mane. It seems to have been removed from where I found it as when I went back for more pictures recently it was no longer there. 

Other species seen: Boneset (Eupatorium perfoliatum), Black Locust (Robinia psuedoacacia), and possibly Bur Oak (Quercus macrocarpa) (I found no acorns, but the leaves are a close match). 

Interactions with other species; The Shaggy Mane Mushroom can be eaten by humans so I would assume other animals may also eat it. As with other fungi, the Shaggy Mane is a decomposer in its environment.
